'''Kunigami Shrine''' (くにがみじんじゃ) is a {{ill|lt=Shinto shrine|Q845945|qid=Q845945|1=Shinto shrine}} located in Maruoka Town, {{ill|lt=Sakai City|Q990342|qid=Q990342|1=Sakai, Fukui}}, {{ill|lt=Fukui Prefecture|Q133879|qid=Q133879|1=Fukui Prefecture}}. Its former shrine rank was prefectural shrine. It enshrines Prince Maruko, a son of {{ill|lt=Emperor Keitai|Q349277|qid=Q349277|1=Emperor Keitai}}.

===History===
Listed as “Kunigami Shrine” of {{ill|lt=Sakai District|Q7402764|qid=Q7402764|1=Sakai District, Fukui}} in the {{ill|lt=Engishiki Jinmyōchō|Q11064932|qid=Q11064932|1=Engishiki Jinmyōchō}}, it is a {{ill|UNKNOWN|lt=Shikinaisha|1=Shikinaisha|qid=Q134917286}} founded before 1200<ref name="board">Information board within the shrine grounds</ref>. According to the shrine tradition recorded in the *Shrine Register*, the shrine originated when the placenta of Prince Maruko, the second son of {{ill|lt=Emperor Keitai|Q349277|qid=Q349277|1=Emperor Keitai}} and Yahime, was buried at the place where the prince was born, called “Maruoko” (磨留古乎加), and a Shinmei shrine was established there<ref name="board" /><ref name="jinjacho">[http://www.jinja-fukui.jp/detail/index.php?ID=20151027_104515 Fukui Prefecture Shrine Association]</ref>.

In {{ill|lt=1576|Q6700|qid=Q6700|1=1576}} (Tenshō 4), when {{ill|lt=Shibata Katsutoyo|Q865901|qid=Q865901|1=Shibata Katsutoyo}} built {{ill|lt=Maruoka Castle|Q1143892|qid=Q1143892|1=Maruoka Castle}} at “Maruoko,” the shrine was relocated from its original site to its present location. Thereafter, it received protection and donations from successive lords of Maruoka Castle<ref name="board" /><ref name="jinjacho" />.

On November 18, {{ill|lt=1874|Q7761|qid=Q7761|1=1874}} (Meiji 7), it was designated a prefectural shrine, and on April 26, {{ill|lt=1908|Q2056|qid=Q2056|1=1908}}, it was specified as a shrine to receive offerings of sacred coins and ritual sticks<ref name="jinjacho" />.

The {{ill|lt=1948|Q5165|qid=Q5165|1=1948}} (Shōwa 23) {{ill|lt=Fukui earthquake|Q4389555|qid=Q4389555|lt=Great Fukui Earthquake|1=1948 Fukui earthquake}} on June 28 caused the shrine buildings and trees to collapse and burn, but on July 15, {{ill|lt=1962|Q2764|qid=Q2764|1=1962}}, the main hall (Shinmei-zukuri), offering hall, and worship hall were rebuilt. In {{ill|lt=1982|Q2436|qid=Q2436|1=1982}}, as a commemorative project marking the 20th anniversary of reconstruction, a treasure hall was newly built and a sacred fence erected<ref name="jinjacho" />.

===Cultural Properties===
Among its many cultural assets are the “Hanging Scroll of the Hakusan Pilgrimage Mandala, color on silk,” dating back to the {{ill|lt=Muromachi period|Q334845|qid=Q334845|1=Muromachi period}} (designated a cultural property of Fukui Prefecture<ref>{{Cite web|ja|author= |year= |url=http://info.pref.fukui.jp/bunka/bunkazai/sitei/kaiga/itiran.html |title=Fukui Prefecture Designated Tangible Cultural Properties (Hanging Scroll of the Hakusan Pilgrimage Mandala, color on silk) |publisher=Fukui Prefecture |accessdate=2018-02-16}}</ref>), as well as the “Heavenly Treasure Sword,” said to have been dedicated by {{ill|lt=Honda Shigeaki|Q10517896|qid=Q10517896|1=Honda Shigeaki}}, lord of Maruoka Castle, and the Senju Kannon of Jambudvīpa gold. Within the shrine grounds is also a stone lantern dedicated by {{ill|lt=Arima Michizumi|Q10517531|qid=Q10517531|1=Arima Michizumi}}, the final lord of the {{ill|lt=Maruoka Domain|Q10863481|qid=Q10863481|1=Maruoka Domain}} who also served as a shogunate {{ill|lt=Rōjū|Q1196812|qid=Q1196812|1=Rōjū}}<ref name="board" />.

===Treasures===
* '''Hanging Scroll of Hakusan Toyohara Mandala, color on silk'''
: Said to have been produced in the Muromachi period, it is regarded as an important historical artifact of {{ill|lt=Hakusan worship|Q11579557|qid=Q11579557|1=Hakusan Faith}}<ref name="岩崎27-28p">{{Cite book|ja|author=Iwasaki Shinnosuke |title=Folk Tales and Legends of Echizen Maruoka |publisher=Iwasaki Shinnosuke |year=1979 |page=27–28 |isbn=}}</ref>.
* '''Heavenly Treasure Sword'''
: A treasured sword dedicated by Honda Shigeaki, lord of Maruoka. The scabbard features {{ill|UNKNOWN|lt=inlay work|1=UNKNOWN}}, and the {{ill|lt=tsuba|Q1758043|qid=Q1758043|1=tsuba}} (handguard) is made of gold. The scabbard is said to be decorated with *kan-shippō*. As of 2019 (Reiwa 1), it is preserved as a treasure of Kunigami Shrine<ref name="岩崎27-28p"/>.
* '''Senju Kannon of Jambudvīpa Gold'''
: In {{ill|lt=862|Q24993|qid=Q24993|1=862}} (Jōgan 4), it was brought back from {{ill|lt=Tang China|Q9683|qid=Q9683|1=Tang dynasty}} by the monk Shinnyo of Settsu and is housed in a {{ill|lt=zushi|Q19993032|qid=Q19993032|1=Zushi}} made of {{ill|UNKNOWN|lt=ebony|1=UNKNOWN}}. Seven ring-like ornaments hang from the halo of the Kannon, with their bases made of gold, silver, and {{ill|lt=shakudō|Q11635994|qid=Q11635994|1=shakudō}}, inlaid with red, blue, and white jewels. The zushi is carved with {{ill|UNKNOWN|lt=lotus flowers|1=UNKNOWN}}, and its curtain is adorned with beautiful gold and {{ill|UNKNOWN|lt=lapis lazuli|1=UNKNOWN}}<ref name="岩崎27-28p"/>.

